- t13. Resistance to Prevention: Reconsidering Feminist Antiviolence Rhetoric / rBurton, Nadya -- tNotes on Contributors -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first anthology to take a theoretical look at violence against women. Each essay shows how philosophy provides a powerful tool for examining a difficult and deep-rooted social problem. Stanley G. French, Wanda Teays, and Laura M. Purdy, all philosophers, present a familiar phenomenon in a new and striking fashion.The editors employ a two-tiered approach to this vital issue. Contributors consider both interpersonal violence, such as rape and battering; and also systemic violence, such as sexual harassment, pornography, prostitution, and violence in a medical context. The editors have further broadened the discussion to include such cross-cultural issues as rape in war, dowry deaths, female genital mutilation, and international policies on violence against women. Against this wide range of topics, which integrate personal perspectives with the philosophical, the contributors offer powerful analyses of the causes and effects of violence against women, as well as potential policies for effecting change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aFamily violence. 0aSexual abuse victims. 0aSexual harassment of women. 0aWomenxCrimes against. 4aGender Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aFrench, Stanley G., eeditor.1 aPurdy, Laura M., eeditor.1 aTeays, Wanda, eeditor.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501724213423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501724213.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-de